For fuller notes and expanded data for each verse, see https://drive.google.com/file/d/1lRbxrC-Sn8CHMsA9t5bTyYb036wz8awM - created by Jamie Jamieson who did most of the programming for creating this data. 

1) Condensed Version - each section with the Tests to identify the versification being followed, and comparison of numbering in different traditions. This version is easy for humans to understand
2) Expanded Version - verse-by-verse renumbering to Standard versification with explanatory notes for each verse. This version is easy for use in software to Standardise a Bible or to add notes about Standard versification to a Bible
     (this version is found below, after the Condensed version and is followed by some more discursive notes)

=================
1) CONDENSED VERSION
=================

FIELD DESCRIPTIONS:
==============
This datasets has multi-line records divided by "$===========". The first line is a Header with Tests that apply to each subsequent subRecord line. SubRecord lines all start with a tab. 
References are recorded in the form of Chap:Verse.Subverse, e.g. Gen.6:1.2 is the second subverse of Gen.6:1 which can also be written as Gen.6:1b. 

The columns headed "English", "Hebrew", "Latin", "Greek" and others contain the equivalent versification for Bibles in these traditions. English is determined by NRSV, Hebrew by MT, Latin by Vulgate, Greek by LXX
Additional columns ("Other") are versions which do not conform to any of these traditions. For example, "Slavonic" follows the Greek tradition except for two passages (Lev.14:55-14:57; Jos.5:14-6:27). 
Additional "undivided" columns are supplied for texts where extra text has not been divided into subverses. 
Some editions of Hebrew, Latin or Greek texts have variations which may conform exactly with another tradition (such as English); if they do not conform with any other tradition their pattern is placed in an additional column. 

Subverses occur when text is added to verses in some Bibles. The text that occurs in that verse in all Bibles is called subverse '0'. Additional verses are called subverse '1', '2' etc. 
        For example, the moving of 6 verses from Jos.8:30-35 to follow Josh.9:2 in Greek Bibles results in the text of Jos.9:2 being numbered Jos.9:2.0 and the moved text being numbered Jos.9:1-6


TEST: 
These examine the points at which the traditions are different. They can be used to determine which tradition is being followed in a specific Bible. 
English Bibles follow mostly the Hebrew tradition, with some differences. Because so many Bibles and most commentaries follow this same set of differences, 
English standard is defined by the NRSV which is virtually identical to KJV (it divides 1Jn.14 to create the extra verse 15). 
East-European or Orthodox Bibles tend to follow the Greek traditions, and West-European or Catholic Bibles tend to follow the Latin tradition. Jewish translations tend to follow the Hebrew tradition. 
However, many Bibles employ a mixture of traditions by following English, Hebrew, Latin or Greek traditional versification for different sections of the Bible. 

Each section has at least 4 columns:  versification numbers in the Standard English, traditional Hebrew, traditional Latin and traditional Greek (and occasionally others)
A Bible is following the numbering in a specific column if the tests above that column are TRUE for that Bible. They may be true for more than one column if these have identical versification. 
* REF.1:30=Last	is TRUE if the Bible has exactly 30 verses in chapter "REF.1"
* REF.1:30=Exist	is TRUE if the Bible has a verse numbered 30 with text in it
* REF.1:30.2=Exist	is TRUE if the Bible has at least 3 subverses in REF.1:30 (the verse that appears in all Bibles is subverse 0)
* REF.1:30=NotExist	is TRUE if the Bible does not have a verse numbered 30 with text in it (and there IS text in the previous verse, if this isn't v.1 - i.e. this chapter didn't end earlier)
* REF.1:30.2=NotExist	is TRUE if the Bible has fewer than 2 subverses in REF.1:30
* REF.1:30>1:29	is TRUE if the Bible has more words in REF.1:30 than in REF.1:29 (this test is designed with enough leeway to work for whatever language the Bible is written in)
* REF.1:30<1:29	is TRUE if the Bible has fewer words in REF.1:30 than in REF.1:29 
* REF.1:30<1:29*2	is TRUE if the Bible has fewer words in REF.1:30 than twice the number of words in REF.1:29
* REF.1:30<1:29.0	is TRUE if the Bible has fewer words in REF.1:30 than in the subverse '0' (i.e. the text which is found in all Bibles, whether or not subverses are added) 
	(subverse 0 is identical to the text found in all Bibles. Additional text that occurs in some Bibles is put into subverse 1 onwards. There are no tests for the length of those subverses because the text may not be divided into subverses)


ALIGNMENTS:
Different types of alignment are created by various situations: 

OT: 
Concatenation	occurs when an English verse merges more than one verse in another Bible, e.g. Exo.28:29
DuplicateTarget	occurs when an English verse contains only part of a verse in another Bible e.g. Gen.50:22-23
OneToOne	occurs a difference causes all subsequent verses are displaced , e.g. Num.12:16-13:33
LongVerse	refers to a section of LXX or Vulgate which is inserted into Standard versification as a series of subverses, e.g. 1Ki.6:1.0-4 (subverse "0" is the normal text of the verse, and 1-4 are additional subverses) 
LongVerseElsewhere	occurs where text has been moved into a LongVerse elsewhere, e.g. Jos.8:30-35
LongVerse/LVElsewhere	occurs where a LongVerse has been created by moving text from elsewhere, e.g. Jos.9:2 
LongVerseDuplicated	occurs where text has been duplicated in a LongVerse elsewhere, e.g. 1Ki.12:23
LongVerse/LVDuplicated 	occurs where a LongVerse has been created by moving text from elsewhere, e.g. 1Ki.12:24
LongVerse/LVExtra	occurs where a LongVerse has been created by adding text to the text, e.g. Est.1:1. These may alternately occur as extra chapters. 
TextMayBeMissing	occurs where some ancient versions do not include any words, e.g. Neh.7:68
StartDifferent	occurs where verse divisions can occur in slightly different positions, e.g. Num.26:1
[= REF]	indicates an alternate way to refer to the same verse in the same Bible


NT: 
TextMayBeMissing	occurs where some ancient manuscripts do not include any words in a verse, e.g. Mat.12:47
PassageMoved	occurs only at Rom.16:25-27 which is found at Rom.14:24-26 in some manuscripts 
Colophon	occurs at the end of epistles, which have a verse about provenance in some manuscripts, e.g. 1Co.16:24
PassageMissing	occurs at the start of passages that are missing in some manuscripts, i.e. Mrk.9-20 & Jhn.7:53-8:11 (& 1Jn.5:7b-8a which does not alter any versification)
StartDifferent	occurs where verse divisions can occur in slightly different positions, e.g. Rev.13:1 
Concatenation	occurs when one verse merges more than one verse in another Bible, e.g. 3Jn.1:14-15]

Occasionally the differences result in a change to verse order. This is marked by an asterix in the top row, e.g."Greek*". This occurs only in Latin "Sir" and in Greek at  Exo.20:13-15; 21.16-17; 35:8-27; 37:1--38:31; 39:32-42; 40:30-31; Num.1:24-25; 10:34; 26:15-47; Jos.24:31; 1Ki.3:1; 4.20-21, 25-28; 6:1; 7:1-12, 21, 25; 9:16, 23-25; 11:5-8; 22:46-49; Jer.31:37; 49:7-39; Ezk.7:3-5; Mal.4:6; (using English verse numbers)
Note: the section "Gen.5:31-6:1" is placed after Malachi for the sole reason that it is the most complex instance of differences, and someone starting to grapple with this data is likely to give up if it is the first one they come across. 


$Section (in Eng refs)	English	Hebrew	Latin	Greek	[Greek2, Slavonic etc.]

=========================================================================================================================================

=================
2) EXPANDED VERSION 
=================


FIELD DESCRIPTIONS:
==============
SourceRef	This is a verse number in a Bible which may be non-Standard, but can also be Standard
StandardRef	This is the equivalent verse number in a Standard Bible IF the tests at the end are TRUE
Action	This is what you do with the text in the verse found in the Source
	- Keep verse = the text retains the same verse number
	- Renumber verse = the text moves to a verse with a different number. If the StandardRef is a subverse (ending in ".1", ".2" etc) then the text is appended to what is already in that verse
	- Empty verse = the verse is likely to be empty, and this is not an error (It may be that there is text in it that has not been moved to another verse, in which case this can be left) 
	- Merged above = the verse is empty because the contents is merged with a verse above
NoteMarker	This is a suggested marker for the note. It is normally the verse number of the most important alternate version. The chapter number is included if it is different to the chapter in the StandardRef
Note 	This is the text of a note that is suited to that version of the Bible at that verse in the StandardRef. This uses standard phrases (listed at the end) bounded by "%" to aid replacement by translated phrases.
SourceType	This isn't used in programming but is useful for checking. It is the type of Bible versification being followed at this verse, and being tested for by the tests.
Tests	These tests have to be TRUE. If they aren't, move on to the next line. There's a section at the end doesn't have any tests, so it applies to that verse in every Bible version. 

See notes at the end on how it works, but briefly: 
eg: at Gen.32:1: if Gen.32:33=Last (ie if v.33 is the last verse in Gen.32) then:
* renumber the verse as Gen.31:55
* add a note: [1] "In some Bibles the verse numbering here is 32:1 (Hebrew=32:1 â¢ Latin=31:55 â¢ Greek=31:55)"

SourceRef	StandardRef	Action	NoteMarker	Note  	SourceType	Tests
==========================================================================================================================================================

How to use this: 
===========
The 1st col has a Bible verse which may need a note and renumbering. If the test(s) in the last col are TRUE, then it needs them. 
Col.2 has the new verse number. If this is the same as the old one, this version of the Bible already has the Standard verse number. The note explains that some Bibles are different. 
Col.3 has the marker for the note, eg "[2]". This is the verse number in the source that is different from the Standard verse number. 
Col 4 has the note to insert at the start of this verse

EG at Gen.32:1, if "Gen.32:33=Last" (ie if v.33 is the last verse in Gen.32) then:
* renumber the verse as Gen.31:55
* add a note: [1] "In some Bibles the verse numbering here is 32:1 (Hebrew=32:1 â¢ Latin=31:55 â¢ Greek=31:55)"
Exo.21:17	Exo.21:16	Renumber verse	[17]	%Normally in this Bible% %the verse numbering here is% 21:17 (Hebrew=21:16 â¢ Latin=21:16 â¢ Greek=21:17)	Greek	21:16<21:17	

EG at Exo.21:17, if "Exo.21:16<21:17" (ie if the number of words in v16 is less than the number in v.17) then renumber the verse and add a note. The difference is picked to be large enough so it will work in any translation. 
EG at 1Ki.6:38, if "1Ki.5:18=Last & 1Ki.6:38=Last & 1Ki.6:1<6:6*2" (ie the chapters end at these verses, and the word-count in v.1 is less than 2x the word-count in v.2

What this produces:
=============
If you renumber verses and add notes whenever the tests are True, this will produce a Bible where:
* Every verse number conforms to Standard versification
* Every verse that is renumbered has a note explaining the fact, with a note-marker that contains the original verse number
* Every verse where ancient translations have different numbering, a note mentions this. This is often important when citing a verse. 

EG in JPS Gen.32:28 And he said unto him: 'What is thy name?' And be said: 'Jacob.'
Becomes: Gen.32:27 [28] And he said unto him: 'What is thy name?' And be said: 'Jacob.'
    note: [28]: Normally in this Bible the verse numbering here is 32:28 (Hebrew=32:28 â¢ Latin=32:27 â¢ Greek=32:27)

EG in ESV Gen.32:27 And he said to him, âWhat is your name?â And he said, âJacob.â
Becomes Gen.32:27 [28] And he said to him, âWhat is your name?â And he said, âJacob.â
    note: [28]: In some Bibles the verse numbering here is 32:28 (Hebrew=32:28 â¢ Latin=32:27 â¢ Greek=32:27)

If you want to produce a Bible with fewer notes, you can
* omit notes when the SourceRef = StandardRef
* omit the summary of ancient refs - ie the sections such as "(Hebrew=32:28 â¢ Latin=32:27 â¢ Greek=32:27)"

If you want to produce a Bible that does not change the verse numbers: 
* don't renumber the verses
* instead of the NoteMarker that is supplied, use the verse number of the StandardRef. 
* use the same note, as given

Psalm Titles
========
In Standard versification, the Titles (when they occur) are the first part of verse 1. However, they are normally formatted in italics, so it is useful if they are distinguished in some way from the rest of the verse. 
In ancient Hebrew, Greek and Latin texts, the Psalm titles are normally in their own verse(s). These are marked as verse ".0" (eg Psa.51:1.0) to indicate that this part of the verse can be put in italics.
Occasionally a long Title may be found in two verses, in which case the contents of the second verse is also labelled ".0" (eg Psa.51:1.0). 
When the first verse of a Psalm has a title, the part of the verse after the Title is called ".1" to indicate there should not be a verse break at this point, but it should be merged into the end of v.1 after the Title. 
LongVerses do not occur in the Psalms, so ".0" in the Psalms indicates a Title, whereas elsewhere it indicates the equivalent text of the Standard verse. 
If an English source has Titles separately, they should be marked as ".0", eg Psa.51:1.0 then Psa.51:1.1 for the contents of the verse


Subverses
=======
EG at Dan.4:34.3 (which is only found in Bibles with subverses, eg editions of the Septuagint) "Dan.4:34=Last & Dan.3:97=Last & Dan.4:34.3=Exist" (ie if chaps 4 & 5 end at v.34 & 39, and if the subverse Dan.4:34.3 does actually exist) then renumber and add a note.

Some versions (esp. the Septuagint and translations of it) have lots of subverses. If they aren't separate in the source, then the tests that are True will follow the "GreekUndivided" scheme. 
So when you are testing for something like Dan.4:34.3, you are looking to see if there is a separate subverse like that. Of course, in some systems, the subverses might be labelled differently - eg. Exo.38:11b - in which case you'll have to conform the text with the rules (or vice versa)

Subverses occur when the LXX moves verses (such as the last few verses of Josh.8) to another place (in this case, just after the text found in Josh.9:2). They are added as subverses at the new location, because if they were inserted as verses, all the subsequent verses would need renumbering. 
So, in this example, the normal text of Josh.9:2 becomes subverse "0" and the inserted verses get numbered as subverses .1-.6 (though some Bibles label them as "a"-"f"). For an example, see p.181 at http://ccat.sas.upenn.edu/nets/edition/06-iesous-nets.pdf

Notional Subverses
=============
Subverses are labelled here as numbers, eg. Exo.28:22.6 - which indicates the 6th verse which has been inserted into the end of Exo.28:22

However there is also a different kind of subverse - a 'notional' subverse - which is labelled with "a" or "b" etc, eg. Exo.28:29b - which indicates a part of a verse and not a proper subverse. 

It occurs, for example, when a single verse in the source Bible is split into two verses in Standard versification, eg: 
Exo.35:17	Exo.35:15	Renumber verse	[15-16]	%Normally in this Bible% %this verse and the next are merged into one verse that is numbered% 35:17 (Hebrew=35:15 â¢ Latin=35:15 â¢ Greek=35:17a)	Greek	Exo.35:16<35:18	
Exo.35:17	Exo.35:16	Merged above	[17b]	%Normally in this Bible% %this verse is merged with the verse above, so the text may be missing here% (Hebrew=35:16 â¢ Latin=35:16 â¢ Greek=35:17b)	Greek	Exo.35:16<35:18	
This results in the whole text for the two verses being put into Exo.35:15 leaving v.16, with nothing but a note explaining what has occurred. In the note, "a" means the first part of the verse, without any indication of where it ends. 

Rearrangements
===========
Subverses usually result in Rearrangements of the text - that is, parts of the text occur in a different order. This almost always occurs in the LXX. We don't know the reason for this, but probably the LXX was translated from an early version of the Hebrew text where the exact order was not yet settled. 
One interesting place is Exo.20:13-15 where the order of some of the 10 Commandments is different, which may be reflected in Jer.7:9. The has yet another order (see https://www.stepbible.org/?q=version=ESV%7Ctext=steal%20and%20adultery%20and%20murder&options=HVNUG&pos=1 )
Some scholars will want to study these texts in the order in which they have been transmitted, but most work on the LXX depends on comparing the translations, for which it is more useful to have the Greek in the same order as the Hebrew, English and Latin. 

Rearrangements also occur in a couple of other places:
â¢ Ben Sirah (or Sirach) has a couple of places in Latin where a few verses are in a different order: 7:9-11; 9:21-23; 10:21-24; 19:25-26; 32:9-11. These are sections of individual sayings, like proverbs, so the order doesn't make any difference to the sense. 
â¢ Rom.14:23 - Byzantine MSS place the 'final' benediction here, though most editions place it at the end of the letter - where almost all translations put it. A notable exception is WEB - see https://www.stepbible.org/?q=version=WEB%7Creference=Rom.14&options=VHNUG&pos=1


Phrases to translate to different languages: 
===========================
%In some Bibles% 
%Normally in this Bible% 
 %this verse includes words that are at% 
 %this verse includes words that are also at% 
 %this verse includes words that are alternately at% 
 %this verse may not contain any text% 
 %this verse starts on a different word% 
 %the verse numbering here is% 
 %this verse and the next are merged into one verse that is numbered% 
%this verse is merged with the verse above, so the text may be missing here%
%Some manuscripts have no text at% 
%At the end of this verse, some manuscripts add information such as where this letter was written%
